I Designed this vast Tribeca office space to feel like a home.  Collecting both vintage and modern pieces from all over the world.  Starting with this beautiful three section sofa from French architect Bismut & Bismut.  I found it strolling the Galleries of Paris in @ecart.international  I had no idea where it was going to go, but the minute I saw this open Loft in Tribeca, I had an immediate flash back to the sofa.  It's fabulous how it creates multiple seating areas. Swipe to see the Before Pic.

The founder of the fastest growing home exercise equipment company wanted her private office to transport her to another world.....a warm layered, cozy world.  We wrapped the walls in a deep blue green sisal and used a gorgeous Dedar silk fabric for the drapes along with the chairs.  For her desk chair, she asked for a show stopper, which we think we hit the mark using this stripped Kelly Wearstler fabric draped on the bias to create dimension.  The lamp is vintage from the 1950s,  and I found it in Italy along with the art piece behind her desk. The fabulous Hermès framed scarf in the third picture mimics the geometric Pierre Frey sofa fabric.  Swipe to see the before picture of what we started with.

This is not a home in Tribeca, but a huge office made to feel like a home.  With vintage and modern furnishings collected from all over the world.  The vintage triangle lamps are French from the 1970s with the original shades. I found them in Paris in the basement of a very famous antiques collector.  I had originally purchased them with the intention to put them in my own home, but when I sourced this huge library table, I knew the lamps would look so perfect flanking it.  So I let them go…..for the love of a project 🩵

Elle Decor June 2018, AD Italia 2023 and AD Middle East 2023.  One of the hardest things to find is a paint color with the perfect undertone.  For this space I was looking for a lavender hue, which came out when I used warm tone light bulbs and brass accents.  In the afternoon, the entire room glows lavender off the French paneled walls designed by @boriesandshearron, which add beautiful dimension.  I have used this Benjamin Moore paint color cement gray in other spaces, yet the lavender has never come out as much as in this room.  So when I am asked for paint color recommendations, I usually have a blank stare on my face because everything is so relative to 🌞 sunlight and the tone of the light bulbs 💡 in every room.  The best advice I can give is to always paint multiple boards and spread them throughout the room so you can see how the light will truly reflect off the color.
